<![CDATA[# Prompt Engineering Cheat Sheet — .cursorrules
# A production-ready template for AI-assisted development
# Full guide: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/blog/ultimate-cursorrules-blueprint-nextjs
#
# Copy this file to your project root to configure AI coding assistants
# (Cursor, GitHub Copilot, etc.) with prompt engineering best practices.

## Project Context
You are working on a Python/TypeScript project that builds, tests, and
deploys LLM-powered applications. The codebase includes prompt templates,
API wrappers, and security utilities for production AI systems.

## Code Style

### Python
- Python 3.11+ with full type annotations (PEP 484/604)
- Follow PEP 8 with a 99-character line length
- Use `from __future__ import annotations` for modern type syntax
- Docstrings in Google style for all public functions and classes
- Prefer `dataclass` or `Pydantic BaseModel` over raw dicts
- Use `pathlib.Path` over `os.path`
- Prefer composition over inheritance

### TypeScript
- Strict TypeScript with no `any` types
- Use `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections
- Prefer `const` assertions and template literal types where applicable
- Use named exports over default exports
- ESLint with recommended rules

### General
- Descriptive variable names reflecting the prompt engineering domain
  (e.g., `system_prompt`, `user_content`, `canary_token`, not `s`, `u`, `t`)
- Maximum function length: 50 lines (extract helpers for longer logic)
- No commented-out code in committed files

## Prompt Engineering Conventions
- Use the STCO framework (Situation, Task, Context, Output) for all prompt templates
  → Guide: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/guides/stco-prompt-framework
- Always define prompts as named constants or template classes, not inline strings
- Include input sanitisation when handling user-provided prompt content
- Use structured output (JSON mode / response_format) when parsing AI responses
- Implement retry logic with exponential backoff for all LLM API calls
- Log all prompts and responses for debugging and auditing (with PII redaction)
- Set explicit `temperature` and `max_tokens` on every API call — no defaults
- Use the model's native role system (system/user/assistant) correctly

## Security — CRITICAL
- Never hardcode API keys — use environment variables or secret managers
- Implement prompt injection defences for all user-facing prompts:
  - XML/delimiter tagging to separate instructions from user data
  - Sandwich defence pattern for user-content-heavy prompts
  - Input sanitisation against known injection patterns
  - Canary tokens in all system prompts
  → Full guide: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/guides/prompt-injection-prevention
- Validate and sanitise ALL user inputs before including in prompts
- Never expose raw model errors to end users
- Rate-limit LLM API calls per user/session
- Implement output filtering for PII, credentials, and internal URLs

## Testing
- Write unit tests for all prompt templates (assert expected structure)
- Include integration tests for API interactions using mocks/recordings
- Test prompt injection resistance with a standard adversarial test suite
- Validate structured output parsing against malformed/edge-case responses
- Test with multiple models when supporting model switching
- Measure and track prompt performance metrics (latency, token usage, quality)

## Error Handling
- Wrap all LLM API calls in try/except with specific exception types
- Implement circuit breakers for API calls (fail fast after N consecutive errors)
- Provide meaningful fallback responses when the LLM is unavailable
- Log errors with full context (prompt name, model, token count, latency)

## Dependencies
- `openai` for OpenAI API access
- `pydantic` for structured output schemas
- `tenacity` for retry logic (preferred over manual retry loops)

## Documentation
- Reference https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/guides for prompt engineering best practices
- Link to STCO framework guide: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/guides/stco-prompt-framework
- Security guidelines: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/guides/prompt-injection-prevention
- Evidence base: https://aipromptarchitect.co.uk/research/prompt-engineering-evidence
